<br>18-year-old Oliver McGowan, mildly autistic, epileptic, and learning disabled, died after being given antipsychotic medication despite his parents and doctors repeatedly telling them he had reacted badly. In this article, we will look back on Oliver’s life story and how his unfortunate death and what we learnt from it help to shape the future of health and social care services.
<br>
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-bBHHxi aumKe pf-22_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-24_">Who was Oliver McGowan?

</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Who_was_Oliver_Mcgowan_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685979151" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Who_was_Oliver_Mcgowan_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685979151 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Who_was_Oliver_Mcgowan_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.png?v=1685979151 320w" width="1796" height="1197" alt="Who was Oliver Mcgowan? - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Who was Oliver Mcgowan? - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-igXgud kyVXGU pf-25_"/><p class="sc-gfqkcP gZrsGP pf-26_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-28_">Born a month premature to Thomas and Paula McGowan, Oliver had rough and challenging early years in the hospital. He had mild hemiplegia, focal partial epilepsy, a mild learning disability, and a diagnosis of high-functioning autism. But these disabilities did not hold him back.
<br><br>As a result of his positive attitude, he amazed everyone with his accomplishments. Oliver achieved the following despite his disabilities:
</span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List" class="sc-bjeSbO eanfEA pf-29_"><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hgKiOD gKSpQd pf-30_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-32_"><font><span><span><span><span>A player on the England Development football squad
<br></span></span></span></span></font></span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hgKiOD gKSpQd pf-33_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-35_">A registered athlete
</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hgKiOD gKSpQd pf-36_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-38_">Ranked 3rd best in the country for track 200 metres

</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hgKiOD gKSpQd pf-39_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-41_">A member of Team Bath and was trained to become a Paralympian

</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hgKiOD gKSpQd pf-42_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-44_">Attained several GCSE and BTEC examinations

</span></li><li data-pf-type="List.Item" class="sc-hgKiOD gKSpQd pf-45_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-47_">Attended a National Star College in Cheltenham.

</span></li></ul><p class="sc-gfqkcP gZrsGP pf-48_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-50_">Among their many compliments were his friendliness, kindness, support for students, and wicked sense of humour. Oliver brought so much happiness and fun. He taught everyone how to look at things differently. Despite his limitations, he never complained.
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-bBHHxi aumKe pf-51_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-53_">Health challenges

</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Health_challenges_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685979458" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Health_challenges_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685979458 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Health_challenges_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.png?v=1685979458 320w" width="1372" height="914" alt="Health challenges - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Health challenges - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-igXgud kyVXGU pf-54_"/><p class="sc-gfqkcP gZrsGP pf-55_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-57_">Oliver was born a month early. He developed bacterial meningitis at three weeks of age. He became very ill, and doctors did not expect him to survive. Nevertheless, he began to recover. Oliver was loved by everyone who met him; he drew people's attention from the very beginning.
<br><br>As a result of an infarction or stroke caused by meningitis, Oliver was left with mild hemiplegia, focal partial epilepsy, a mild learning disability and later on, a diagnosis of high-functioning autism. According to the family's neurologist, Oliver had a full life expectancy and was expected to live independently with little support.<br>
<br>However, Oliver was admitted numerous times after suffering seizures. We will discuss these situations below.
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-bBHHxi aumKe pf-58_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-60_">Oliver’s health challenges: 2015

</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_s_health_challenges_2015_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685980287" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_s_health_challenges_2015_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685980287 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_s_health_challenges_2015_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.png?v=1685980287 320w" width="1805" height="1205" alt="Oliver’s health challenges: 2015 - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Oliver’s health challenges: 2015 - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-igXgud kyVXGU pf-61_"/><p class="sc-gfqkcP gZrsGP pf-62_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-64_">Oliver was admitted to a children’s hospital in October 2015. He was experiencing partial focal seizures and felt scared and confused. He was discharged after a few weeks and given antidepressants.
<br><br>After taking these medications, his mood changed, and he started having seizures more frequently. This led to him being admitted back to the same hospital in December of that same year, only this time he was given antipsychotic medications.
<br><br>Oliver's situation was catastrophic. His seizure threshold and agitation deteriorated, leading to him being held against his will under section 2 of the Mental Health Act to undergo assessments. His mood and seizure activity returned to normal within days when the antipsychotic medication was removed, and he was discharged back home. The discharge consultant psychiatrist noted that Oliver was sensitive to antipsychotics.
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-bBHHxi aumKe pf-65_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-67_">Oliver’s health challenges: 2016
</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_s_health_challenges_2016_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_-1.png?v=1685980659" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_s_health_challenges_2016_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_-1.png?v=1685980659 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_s_health_challenges_2016_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_-1_500x.png?v=1685980659 320w" width="1344" height="896" alt="Oliver’s health challenges: 2016 - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Oliver’s health challenges: 2016 - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-igXgud kyVXGU pf-68_"/><p class="sc-gfqkcP gZrsGP pf-69_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-71_">Oliver was readmitted to the same hospital in April 2016, suffering from simple partial seizures. Unbelievably, Oliver was again prescribed antipsychotic medications despite what happened last time. He had Oculogyric Crisis, a serious dystonic side effect causing his eyes to roll upwards. A procyclidine injection was administered to counteract the reaction, which was left like this for six hours as the doctor initially believed it was behavioural.
<br><br>Again, Oliver’s mood changed significantly. He was hallucinating, having up to 30 seizures daily, had problems urinating, extremely high blood pressure readings and sweating. Doctors and nurses seemed to have minimal knowledge of autism and how it might manifest in someone with ongoing seizures.
<br><br>In an effort to better understand Oliver's epilepsy, his parents requested he be transferred to a specialist adult hospital. He had received a letter that detailed his reactions to previous medications. The hospital was highly intolerant of Oliver's autistic and learning disabled behaviours.
<br><br>After being treated with different antipsychotic medications, he was detained against his will under Section 2 for assessment and transferred to a specialist PICU for mental health. Upon seeing that he did not need to be detained, the staff immediately reduced all antipsychotic medications. He received support from a specialist learning disability team and was again given a letter saying that he was sensitive to antipsychotics and benzodiazepines.
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-bBHHxi aumKe pf-72_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-74_">Oliver and his last fighting moments
</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_and_his_last_fighting_moments_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685980868" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_and_his_last_fighting_moments_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685980868 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Oliver_and_his_last_fighting_moments_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.png?v=1685980868 320w" width="1280" height="720" alt="Oliver and his last fighting moments - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Oliver and his last fighting moments - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-igXgud kyVXGU pf-75_"/><p class="sc-gfqkcP gZrsGP pf-76_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-78_">Oliver was admitted to a different general hospital in October 2016 after experiencing a cluster of partial seizures. His medical care and drug charts were written in bold red ink that he was intolerant to antipsychotic medications, as illustrated by the supporting letters, including his Hospital Passport. An email was also sent to all doctors treating Oliver after the incident in A&amp;E.
<br><br>He was intubated and developed pneumonia later on. In the following days, Oliver developed a temperature of 42° and had elevated liver function. No medication was prescribed for him except a blow-up mattress filled with cold air. The doctors sent him for a scan of his liver and lungs. He was now having tonic-clonic seizures despite heavy sedation and paralysis drugs.
<br><br>As one of Oliver's pupils reacted very slowly, doctors sent him for an emergency MRI scan of his brain two days later. When Oliver returned, the doctors told his parents that his brain was so swollen that it bulged out of his skull. Neurosurgeons and emergency doctors suspected a neuroleptic malignant syndrome - a serious side effect of antipsychotic medications.
<br><br>Oliver’s brain was now so severely damaged that he would be profoundly disabled, with no speech, understanding of language, or way of communicating. He would rely on a tracheostomy and be tube-fed for the rest of his life. Oliver was now paralysed.
<br><br>A week later, the decision was made to turn Oliver’s life support machines off. Oliver passed away several days later on Armistice Day, 11th November 2016.
<br>
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-bBHHxi aumKe pf-79_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-81_">The aftermath of Oliver’s death

</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_aftermath_of_Oliver_s_death_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_27d02742-28e0-4b9b-8ff4-cb57c7b3e532.png?v=1686151572" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_aftermath_of_Oliver_s_death_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_27d02742-28e0-4b9b-8ff4-cb57c7b3e532.png?v=1686151572 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_aftermath_of_Oliver_s_death_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_27d02742-28e0-4b9b-8ff4-cb57c7b3e532_500x.png?v=1686151572 320w" width="1440" height="960" alt="The aftermath of Oliver’s death - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="The aftermath of Oliver’s death - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-igXgud kyVXGU pf-82_"/><p class="sc-gfqkcP gZrsGP pf-83_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-85_">A life was wasted because doctors failed to communicate effectively with his family and other practitioners who knew him well and were in daily contact with the hospital. 
<br><br>Oliver’s parents believe that his death could have been prevented. Oliver was given excessive drugs due to medical staff not understanding how autism impacts seizure activity. Instead of adapting the environment to meet his needs, excessive restraint methods were used. They failed to communicate with community-based professionals who were working with Oliver daily.<br>
<br>Oliver's death highlighted the need for health and social care staff to know and understand the needs of people with autism and learning disabilities.
<br>

</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-bBHHxi aumKe pf-86_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-88_">The Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training on Learning Disability and Autism

</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_on_Learning_Disability_and_Autism_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685981156" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_on_Learning_Disability_and_Autism_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.png?v=1685981156 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_on_Learning_Disability_and_Autism_-_Oliver_McGowan_Mandatory_Training_-_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.png?v=1685981156 320w" width="1507" height="1067" alt="The Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training on Learning Disability and Autism - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="The Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training on Learning Disability and Autism - Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training - Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-igXgud kyVXGU pf-89_"/><p class="sc-gfqkcP gZrsGP pf-90_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jdhwqr jnAcXR pf-92_">The training is named after Oliver McGowan. Oliver McGowan Mandatory Training on Learning Disability and Autism aims to provide the social care and health workforce with skills and knowledge to provide safe, compassionate and informed care to autistic and learning disabled people. The government recommended training for health and social care staff on learning disabilities and autism.
<br><br>Regulations introduced by the Health and Care Act 2022 require regulated service providers to ensure their staff receive training appropriate to their role on learning disabilities and autism. This training will ensure that people with learning disabilities and autism spectrum conditions have access to the skills and expertise they need.<br>
